            <h2>Laoag City</h2>
            <h3>The Sunshine City</h3>

            <img src="<?= $this->webroot ?>theme/weatherph/img/tourism/laoagCity1.png" alt="">

            <p>Laoag City, the Northern Gateway to the Philippines, is located at the west-central side of Ilocos Norte in Northern Philippines. It is the capital of Ilocos Norte province.</p>
            <p>A vibrant and dynamic growth center in the North, the City offers a unique experience to tourists such as the panoramic La Paz sand dunes, historical and heritage sites, lush vegetation, scenic beaches, and highland lures.</p>
            <p>The City’s tourist and cultural destinations have been nationally recognized like the Grand National Champion in 2004, 2006, 2008 in the Aliwan Float Competition during the Aliwan Festivals. It was also awarded as Champion in the Best Booth Competition at the 18th Philippine Travel Mart in 2007 and awarded by the Department of Tourism and Association of Tourism Officers of the Philippines as first runner up, Best in Cultural Festival with Pamulinawen Festival as the city’s entry in 2009.</p>
            <p>Laoag City is one of the most liveable city and was adjudged as the fifth Most Livable City in the Philippines in the Philippine Cities Competitiveness Ranking Project by the Asian Institute of Management Policy Center. In 2010, Laoag City received the biggest number of local and foreign tourists, students on their field trips, and employees and officials of local governments and nongovernment organizations on their Lakbay–Aral sessions.</p>
            <p>For its part, the City government has invested heavily on health and environmental projects. The old City Hospital was trans- formed into a 120-bed secondary, ultra-modern Medical Center. The City’s sanitary landfill has been converted into Sunshine City Material Recovery Facility where most waste materials are processed into organic fertilizer and building materials such as pavers and hollow blocks. Eco-friendly E-taxi, electronic jeeps and Smart bikes are being used by the police and traffic enforcers in their daily patrols.</p>

