            <h3>Laoag City’s Must Do List</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>1. Visit the St. William Cathedral, one of the biggest churches of the country. This 400- year old structure showcases the Spanish era and its impact on the Ilocano architecture and culture. The church’s belfry, the Sinking Bell Tower, is one of the city’s top attractions. It is said that a rider atop his horse could enter this edifice but has now sunk considerably that one must stoop low to be able to view its magnificent threshold.</li>
                <li>2. Get to learn more about the City’s past through the Tobacco Monopoly, an obelisk of clay brick. This monument is the Ilocano’s way of thanking King Alfonso XII of Spain for rescinding the Monopoly. It stands prominently at the Aurora Park located at the foot of the magnificent Gilbert Bridge.</li>
                <li>3. Feel the sand dunes in La Paz, a rare geological monument. This vast sand dune formation (the only one in the Philip- pines) offers a fine vista of the West Philippine Sea (South China Sea). It is a continually shifting body of sand that is prone to erosion. It is a favorite destination of 4x4 off road enthusiasts.</li>
                <li>4. Stay in The Fort Ilocandia Resort and Casino, a five-star hotel in Northern Luzon. The resort is complete with different amenities designed to provide absolute satisfaction for the tourist and traveler alike. Explore The Museo Ilocos Norte as it showcases the varied ethnicity and multi-faceted cultural heritage of a sturdy, hard-working people known for their industry, resourcefulness, and loyalty.</li>
                <li>5. Fill in your taste buds with the best of Ilocano cuisine. Signature vegetable dish include Pinakbet, a mix of fresh veg- etables steamed in fish sauce, the Longaniza or garlic-flavored pork sausage, and Bagnet (pan-fried pork meat). There are also equally tasty snacks and desserts such as Chichacorn (corn bits), Empanada (Latin-inspired fried bread dough stuffed with grated papaya and whole egg), Bibingka (oven-baked sticky rice cake), Tupig (sticky rice with young coconut in banana leaves), and Artem (pickels in sukang iloko).</li>
            </ol>

